Languages, as an optional subject, are now considered as important in independent school programs and elsewhere as basic subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
According to a survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons for employers' difficulties in filling jobs were lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming mandatory so that young people are prepared for their future career.
As future access to employment will depend to a large extent on languages, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses, his or her second language will in future be far superior to others if he or she has these lifelong skills.
By being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person learning several languages will be much more competitive.
According to a 2013 survey conducted by YouGov, involving more than 4 000 UK adults, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to take part in the interview, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, i.e. 15 percent.
