In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt's goal was to take control of the world.
“We have to do it now,” he said about the start-up.
- It's a historical moment."
The Solid-based app allows people to create their own personal online data store – POD.
It may contain lists, to-do lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal or work tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are available in one browser at the same time.
The personal data online store is unique in that it is up to the user to decide who and which information can be accessed.
The company calls it personal empowerment through data.
According to John Bruce, CEO of the company, the idea of Inrupt is to provide resources, processes and the necessary skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
Currently the company consists of T. Berners-Lee, J. Bruce, a safety platform purchased by IBM, several programmers hired to work with this project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Since this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools provided on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not in agreement with Facebook or Google about changes that turn all business models upside down overnight.
"We are not asking for their permission."
In a report published by Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee writes that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the durability and quality of the new Solid-based network."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet after founding the Web Consortium at Massachusetts University of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had an influential opinion in discussions about Internet neutrality.
Even working with Inrupt Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
