National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
A new study conducted at a Scottish highland estate aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The findings are expected to provide new knowledge of the behavior of unique flying mammals and provide some guidance for future conservation activities.
Researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will observe the dwarfs, soprano bats, brown abalones and water mouses in the gardens of Wester Ross Inverev in their research.
Special recorders will be placed in certain areas of the area, allowing to track bat activity throughout the season.
National Health Service staff and volunteers will also perform mobile tests with handheld detectors.
The expert analysis of all sound recordings will determine the frequency of signals emitted by bats and the type of activity.
A map and report of residential habitats will then be created to help shape a detailed behavioural picture on the scale of the entire landscape.
National Trust for Scotland (NTS) conservation adviser Rob Dewar hopes that the results will reveal which habitat is most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help identify the benefits of residential habitat maintenance, such as the creation of grasslands, as well as how best to look after wooded areas to be suitable for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined.
They are threatened by construction and real estate development works affecting hatcheries and destroying residential habitats.
Wind turbines and lightning are also a threat, as are ours, some chemicals used to process construction materials, as well as hunting domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, ears are more helpful than eyes to catch prey during night hunting.
Bats accurately determine the location of insects or obstacles in the flight path by an elaborate echolocation method.
The NTS, which is responsible for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land nationwide, is extremely responsible towards bats.
There are ten trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, hatchery inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only reserve specifically for bats in Scotland in Damfries and the Threeve Manor in Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten bat species live.
Manor caretaker David Thompson says the manor area is ideal for them.
“We have a great place for bats at Threeave Manor,” he said.
– We have old buildings, many mature trees and great areas to live in.
However, we still do not know much about bats, so work here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what they need in order to thrive."
He emphasizes that it is essential to check for bats before the site's maintenance work begins, as the accidental destruction of one hatchery could kill up to 400 females and juveniles, which could lead to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats shall be protected and shall be prohibited from being killed, teased or disturbed, as well as from destroying their hatcheries.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer of the Scottish Fund for Bat Protection, urged the public to contribute to the rescue of the batsmen.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we don't even know how many populations of native species are going."
