The most notable controversy occurred this week when new tariffs came into force that would affect goods worth 200 billion dollars (150 billion pounds), i.e. in principle half of China's exports to the US will be taxed.
Beijing responded to all the measures at the same time, with the latest decision imposing a five to ten percent duty on American goods with a total value of $60 billion.
China has vowed to fight the US tooth for a tooth, and it seems that this second largest world market is certainly not going to land in the near future.
Washington would only relax sanctions if China complied with the demands, but publicly bowing to the US would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its party properly, the difficulties of the trade war with the US may eventually have a positive impact on China as it will reduce the interdependence of these markets.
"The fact that a sudden political decision in Washington, D.C. or Beijing can create conditions that would disrupt the economy of both countries is indeed far more dangerous than observers have recognised so far," said Abigail Grace, a researcher at the "Asia New American Security Center".
According to the Syrian Foreign Minister, the country is ready to accept returning refugees
Syria claims to be ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help in rebuilding a country devastated by more than 7 years of war.
Speaking at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country were improving.
"The progress in the fight against terrorism has made the situation in the territory much more stable and secure," he said.
The government continues its efforts to rebuild the areas destroyed by terrorists and to restore normality.
All the conditions are already in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they have had to leave behind because of terrorism and unilateral economic sanctions against daily life and prosperity.
The UN estimates that around 5.5 million Syrians have left Syria since the outbreak of the war in 2011.
Six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would be happy to accept assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he also stressed that the country would not accept conditional support or assistance from countries supporting the uprising.
